<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How much does a bathroom remodel cost?", answer: "National averages put a minor bathroom refresh at 3,000-7,000 dollars, a midrange remodel at 10,000-25,000, a major gut remodel at 25,000-50,000, and a luxury remodel at 50,000-100,000+. Per square foot, that is roughly 125 dollars for minor, 275 for midrange, 425 for major, and 650+ for luxury. A typical 40 sq ft bathroom at midrange runs 11,000 to 15,000 dollars; at major, 17,000 to 22,000." },
  { question: "What's included in the different tiers?", answer: "Minor: paint, new fixtures (faucets, lighting), new toilet, re-caulk, new mirror and accessories. Midrange: new vanity, new counters, new flooring, possibly new tub/shower surround. Major: full gut, tile everything, new tub or walk-in shower, new plumbing, new electrical, new windows. Luxury: custom vanity, heated floors, curbless walk-in shower, frameless glass, high-end fixtures, smart toilets, heated towel rails." },
  { question: "Why is a bathroom remodel so expensive per square foot?", answer: "Bathrooms pack more plumbing, electrical, waterproofing, tile, and finish work into fewer square feet than any other room in the house. A 40 sq ft bathroom has the same number of plumbing fixtures as a 150 sq ft kitchen, plus tile on floors and walls, plus waterproofing. The per-sqft rate is higher but the total cost is usually lower because the room is small." },
  { question: "Where does the money go?", answer: "Roughly: labor 25 percent, fixtures 20 percent, tile and flooring 20 percent, cabinetry 15 percent, plumbing rough-in 10 percent, lighting and electrical 5 percent, other 5 percent. Labor is the biggest line because bathroom work is detailed and skilled — waterproofing, tile setting, plumbing, and electrical all require pros. DIY demo and painting can save 1,000-2,000 dollars, but leave the rest to licensed trades unless you're experienced." },
  { question: "Does a bathroom remodel add value?", answer: "Remodeling Magazine's 2024 Cost vs Value Report shows bathroom remodels recoup 60 to 70 percent at resale for midrange, 55 percent for major, and 50 percent for luxury. Like kitchens, they pay off in lifestyle even when resale ROI is less than 100 percent. Adding a second bathroom to a 1-bath home has the best ROI because 1-bath homes are hard to sell — roughly 80 to 90 percent payback." }
]) %>

